66", "date": "1991-04-28", "label": "Carnegie Hall Centennial Festival: A Celebration of Jazz: The Carnegie Hall Jazz Band", "venue": "Main Hall", "roles": ["trumpet"], "works": [{"t": "Things to Come", "c": "Dizzy Gillespie", "w": "38474"}, {"t": "A Night in Tunisia", "c": "Dizzy Gillespie", "w": "38193"}, {"t": "'Round Midnight", "c": "Thelonious Monk", "w": "23514"}]}, {"id": "6337", "date": "1991-06-25", "label": "JVC Jazz Festival: Tribute to Sarah Vaughan", "venue": "Main Hall", "roles": ["trumpet"], "works": [{"t": "Selections (unspecified)", "c": null, "w": "104450"}]}], "works_created": [{"t": "Brother Martin", "w": "74098"}, {"t": "Ooh-Shoo-Be-Doo-Bee", "w": "108153"}, {"t": "Salt Peanuts", "w": "33733"}, {"t": "Blue 'n Boogie", "w": "10334"}, {"t": "Tin Tin Deo", "w": "122542"}, {"t": "Ow!", "w": "29364"}, {"t": "Shaw 'Nuff", "w": "30839"}, {"t": "A Night in Tunisia", "w": "115970"}, {"t": "Diddy Wa Diddy (Mozambique)", "w": "107053"}, {"t": "Cool Breeze", "w": "42819"}, {"t": "The Champ", "w": "84421"}, {"t": "I Waited for You", "w": "5761"}, {"t": "Dizzy Atmosphere", "w": "3536"}, {"t": "Things to Come", "w": "38474"}, {"t": "Manteca", "w": "22454"}, {"t": "The Burning Spear", "w": "104407"}, {"t": "Con Alma", "w": "16015"}, {"t": "Bye", "w": "107055"}, {"t": "Groovin' High", "w": "34250"}, {"t": "A Night in Tunisia", "w": "38193"}, {"t": "Ool-Ya-Koo", "w": "25321"}, {"t": "Bebop", "w": "74075"}, {"t": "Tunisian Fantasy", "w": "16995"}, {"t": "Wheatleigh Hall", "w": "74207"}, {"t": "Rhumbop Concerto", "w": "59385"}, {"t": "Olinga", "w": "107054"}, {"t": "Selection (unspecified)", "w": "74071"}, {"t": "Woody 'n' You", "w": "30167"}, {"t": "Oopapada", "w": "9241"}, {"t": "Emanon", "w": "39499"}, {"t": "Dizzy's Blues", "w": "84418"}, {"t": "This Is The Way", "w": "45536"}, {"t": "Birk's Works", "w": "5212"}, {"t": "Kush, An African Poem", "w": "14580"}, {"t": "Behind the Curtain Blues", "w": "84417"}], "quotes": [], "about_quotes": [{"speaker": "Ray Brown", "relation": "played under", "confidence": 1.0, "evidence": "So Dizzy said to me, “You want a job?” And I said — “Yeah.” ... So I go to Dizzy Gillespie’s house the next day ... And then they started to play ... But anyway he said, “Okay you’ll do.” We are going to work ... I said, “I’m with Dizzy Gillespie.”", "doc_title": "Ray Brown interviewed by Monk Rowe, Scottsdale, AZ, April 16, 2000", "collection": "hamilton", "url": "https://litsdigital.hamilton.edu/collections/object/ray-brown-interviewed-monk-rowe-scottsdale-az-april-16-2000"}, {"speaker": "Jerry Bergonzi", "relation": "knows of", "confidence": 1.0, "evidence": "The interviewer mentions 'Dizzy Gillespie with the beret' as a cultural symbol of the 50s; the interviewee does not mention Dizzy Gillespie in their response, nor does the transcript contain any other mention of Dizzy Gillespie.", "doc_title": "Jerry Bergonzi interviewed by Monk Rowe, via Zoom, June 7, 2022", "collection": "hamilton", "url": "https://litsdigital.hamilton.edu/collections/object/jerry-bergonzi-interviewed-monk-rowe-zoom-june-7-2022"}, {"speaker": "Leonard Phillips", "relation": "knows of", "confidence": 1.0, "evidence": "The interviewee discusses Leo Williams' relationship with Dizzy Gillespie ('He played first alto with Diz, when Diz had his first band'), but does not describe a personal relationship between himself and Dizzy Gillespie.", "doc_title": "56422_Leonard Phillips oral history interview", "collection": "rutgers", "url": "https://rucore.libraries.rutgers.edu/rutgers-lib/56422/"}, {"speaker": "Tom Porrello", "relation": "knows of", "confidence": 1.0, "evidence": "I like what Dizzy Gillespie always said, “the trumpet — one day you play the trumpet and you win. The next day you play the trumpet the trumpet wins. Then you die and the trumpet wins again.” That was Dizzy’s quote.", "doc_title": "Tom Porrello interviewed by Monk Rowe, via Zoom, March 6, 2023", "collection": "hamilton", "url": "https://litsdigital.hamilton.edu/collections/object/tom-porrello-interviewed-monk-rowe-zoom-march-6-2023"}, {"speaker": "Kenny Burrell", "relation": "played under", "confidence": 1.0, "evidence": "So I mean, I framed my first paycheck... I’m so excited to be playing with Dizzy Gillespie in 1951... Dizzy was a great teacher; he was like a father figure to many many musicians, including myself.", "doc_title": "Kenny Burrell — Smithsonian Jazz Oral History", "collection": "si", "url": "https://amhistory.si.edu/jazz/Burrell-Kenny/Burrell_Kenny_Transcript.pdf"}, {"speaker": "Yusef Lateef", "relation": "played under", "confidence": 1.0, "evidence": "Diz sent for me to join the band. I joined them in San Francisco, and I stayed with them for about two years... I was watching Dizzy Gillespie, who was in front of the band", "doc_title": "Yusef Lateef — Smithsonian Jazz Oral History", "collection": "si", "url": "https://amhistory.si.edu/jazz/Lateef-Yusef/Yusef-Lateef_transcription.pdf"}]}